PART 2: FOR LATER CONCERNS (Post-Launch)
1. Security (Defer Until Multi-User)
Suggestion	Why Defer
API Key Redaction in Logs	You're the only person seeing the logs. Even if API keys appear in logs, you're the one who owns them. Not a risk until multiple people access logs.
Data Retention Policy	You can manually clean up old data if it becomes a problem. No need to build automated policies until you have real users generating significant data.
IP-Based Rate Limiting	With only one user (you), rate limits are already enforced by provider quotas. IP limits add complexity with zero benefit.
Content Safety Check	You're not going to abuse your own system or enter harmful content. This is only needed when untrusted users join.
Opt-Out Header for Training	While some providers (Gemini, DeepSeek) may use your data for training, you're the only user. You can decide for yourself if this matters. Add the opt-out header when you care about data privacy.
2. Multi-User Features (Defer Until Real Users)
Suggestion	Why Defer
User ID Tracking	Only one user. You know who you are. No need to distinguish.
Quota Dashboard Endpoint	You can check provider dashboards directly (Groq console, Google AI Studio, NVIDIA build portal). No need to build a custom endpoint yet.
Performance Metrics Endpoint	You can check logs manually. Add this only when you need historical trends or want to share metrics.
Slack/Email Alerts	You'll notice if the app breaks—you're the one using it. Alerts are only needed when you're not actively monitoring.
Pre-Flight Quota Check	Nice-to-have, but 429 errors are handled gracefully by the fallback chain. You can add this when you care about saving 60 seconds of failover latency (which only matters at scale).
3. Infrastructure (Defer Until Scale)
Suggestion	Why Defer
Job Persistence to PostgreSQL	In-memory ConcurrentHashMap is perfectly fine for a single user. If the app restarts, you'll just regenerate the roadmap. No data loss—it's all regeneratable. Add persistence only when users can't afford to lose job state.
Distributed Caching	Caffeine in-memory cache is fine for one user. No need for Redis or distributed solutions until multiple users share a cache.
Horizontal Scaling	One instance is enough. No need to think about scaling until you have concurrent users.
Database Indexing	With only one user, the database handles queries instantly. Indexing is an optimization for multi-user query loads.
4. Advanced AI Features (Defer Until Quality Becomes Critical)
Suggestion	Why Defer
Hybrid 8B vs 49B Ensemble	Adds model selection complexity. Start with a single model per tier. If you hit quality issues, you can revisit this.
SME Critique Loop	Adds 1-2 extra AI calls per career roadmap. Only critical if you're generating career paths and want to catch hallucinations. Defer until you have real career path users.
Dynamic Re-Forecasting	Requires session history data. You won't have enough data until you've used the app for a while. Defer until you have at least 10-20 completed sessions per roadmap.
Retroactive Alignment	Complex logic involving project detection and patch generation. Defer until users actually finish projects and you can see if tech-stack drift is a real problem.
Proactive Nudges	Requires tuning to avoid being annoying. Defer until you have real usage patterns and can observe what's helpful vs. intrusive.
Dependency Risk + Bridges	Advanced graph logic. Defer until you see real dependency issues (e.g., users struggling with specific transitions).
Double-Check Heavy	Adds a Gemini Pro call. Defer until career paths are actually being generated and you want to validate quality.
Project Validation (AI Review)	Complex and quota-intensive. Defer until users are actually completing projects and want feedback.
5. Testing (Defer Until Code is Stable)
Suggestion	Why Defer
Regression Tests with Golden Prompts	While you're actively iterating on prompts, golden tests will constantly break. Add them once prompts are stable.
WireMock Integration	Mockito is simpler for a solo developer. WireMock adds complexity without benefit. Add it only when you need to simulate API behaviors at scale.
Performance/Load Testing	Only one user. No need.
6. Observability (Defer Until Needed)
Suggestion	Why Defer
Detailed Metrics Endpoint	You can check logs. Add this only when you need a dashboard or want to share performance data.
Failed Job Prompt Storage	You can debug locally. No need to store failed prompts until you have users reporting issues.
Alerting System	You're the only user. You'll notice if it breaks. Alerts are only needed when you're not actively using it.
7. UI/UX Polish (Defer Until Core Works)
Suggestion	Why Defer
Collapsible Modules by Default	Nice-to-have, but you can manually collapse modules. Defer until the roadmap tree gets deep enough to be overwhelming.
Timeline Visualization	Visual polish. Defer until you have enough roadmaps to make a timeline meaningful.
Project Validation (AI Review)	Complex and quota-intensive. Defer until users are actually completing projects and want feedback.
Advanced Breadcrumb Styling	Basic breadcrumb is enough for now. Style it more later.
8. Advanced UI/UX (Defer Until Multi-Module)
Suggestion	Why Defer
Drag-and-Drop Reorder	Nice-to-have but adds significant complexity. Use the current reorder mode (toggle + arrow buttons) until you need more.
Collapsible Completed Phases	Simple toggle is enough for now. Full collapsible UI can come later.
Module Progress Indicators	Basic progress bar is enough. Phase-level indicators can come later.
Resource Categorization	Simple list is fine. Categorization (video/article/interactive) can be added later.
